            About Me
            I am currently a PhD student at the Paris School of Economics and a teaching fellow at the École Normale Supérieure. My PhD supervisor is Hélène Ollivier (CNRS-PSE).
            I am currently on the job market.
            My thesis focuses on improving causal inference methods to better measure the effects of air pollution on health. I am particularly interested in matching procedures and randomization-based inference. I enjoy programming in R and I am always looking for new ways to improve my data visualization skills.
            In my job market paper with Vincent Bagilet (PhD student, Columbia University), we explore how several causal inference methods perform to estimate the effects of air pollution on short-term mortality and morbidity. Specifically, we use simulations to understand why research designs could be under-powered and thereby produce inflated estimates. We propose simple recommendations to take into account statistical power issues.
            
          
        
      
    

    
      
        
          
            
              
            
